SOLID Principles:
-->REduce tight coupling
-->Increase code Reusability
-->Make code easy to maintain
-->clean Architecture
-->set of design rules to make software flexible

where we can use ?
-->java/OOP-based Projects
-->BackEnd Applications
-->Large Enterprise applications
-->Microservices

----------------------------------------------------

S--->Single Responsibility Principle:

A class should have one reason to change.
one class---one responsibility

-------------------------------------------------------

O-->Open / Closed Principle

software entities open for extension,
closed for modification.
-->you can add new behaviour.
-->without changing existing code.
-->Use Interfaces and Abstract classes.

-------------------------------------------------------

L-->Liskov Substitution Principle

Child class Object Should be replaceable
for parent class without breaking behaviour.

-->subclass should behave like parent.
-->dont force child classes to implement invalid methods.

-------------------------------------------------------

I-->Interface Segregation Principle

Clients should not be forced to implement interfaces they don't use

-->create small ,Specific Interfaces
-->Not one big interface
-->prefer Multiple Interfaces

------------------------------------------------------------

D-->Dependency Inversion Principle

High level Modules should not depend on low level modules.
Both depend on Abstraction

-->Depend on Interfaces,not Concrete Classes

-----------------------------------------------------------

SRP--> One Class---One Responsibility
OCP--> open for Extend,close for modification
LSP--> Subclass must Behave like Parent
ISP-->Many Small Interfaces
DIP-->Depend on interfaces,not Classes.
